<Base title="About" active="about">
  <article class="page-narrow">
    <h1>About Codex</h1>

    <p>
      Codex is a three-tier interactive curriculum. The same mathematical concept lives in a single document at three reading levels, and the reader picks the level that matches their preparation.
    </p>

    <h2>The tier model</h2>

    <h3>Beginner</h3>
    <p>
      Strogatz / 3Blue1Brown sensibility. Geometric pictures, worked numerical examples, multiple-choice checks for understanding, no advanced symbols. The goal is intuition, not formalism.
    </p>

    <h3>Intermediate</h3>
    <p>
      A formal definition, a key theorem with proof, seven exercises mixing easy / medium / hard with hints and full answers, and a Lean formalization stub linking to the relevant Mathlib infrastructure.
    </p>

    <h3>Master</h3>
    <p>
      Graduate-textbook depth. Advanced results connecting the concept to current research; full proof set or pointers to one; cross-references to adjacent concepts; historical context citing the original papers in the precise framing the originator used; bibliography pulling from the canonical literature.
    </p>

    <h2>Quality gate</h2>
    <p>
      Every unit passes a 27-point automated rubric covering: frontmatter completeness, prerequisite resolution, reference integrity, prose constraints (no "obviously" / "clearly" / "trivially" — these are confessions, not arguments), tier-marker structure, formal-section coverage, and bibliographic completeness. The build fails if any unit slips.
    </p>

    <h2>Source pairing</h2>
    <p>
      Each unit cites two reference layers: the <strong>originator paper</strong> where the concept was conceived, and the <strong>modern textbook anchor</strong>, ideally drawn from the Fast Track booklist. Where the original paper is readable in 2026 (Cauchy 1825, Riemann 1851/1857, Cartan 1894, Hodge 1941, Frobenius 1896, Weyl 1925, Mumford 1965), Master-tier prose mines the original framing rather than only the modern synthesis. The intent: convey the intelligence of the people who first saw these ideas.
    </p>

    <h2>Lean formalization</h2>
    <p>
      Each unit is paired with a Lean stub at <code>lean/Codex/&lt;path&gt;</code>, with a <code>lean_status</code> tag of <code>full</code> (Mathlib has the result), <code>partial</code> (Mathlib has related infrastructure), or <code>none</code> (Mathlib has no related material). Mathlib gaps are tracked per unit so contributors can see where formalization work is wanted.
    </p>

    <h2>Status</h2>
    <p>
      Curriculum content is shipped and validated. The site you're reading is the v0.1 reading layer. Future versions will add reading-progress persistence, dependency-graph visualisation, RAG-backed search, and concept catalog browsing.
    </p>

    <h2>Reading paths</h2>
    <p>
      No single linear path. Unit prerequisites form a directed acyclic graph; you can enter at any unit whose prerequisites you've already cleared and explore outward. The unit index is the easiest entry point; deep readers can browse the dependency map (forthcoming).
    </p>
  </article>
</Base>
